I am currently getting:

Foo.js:10: WARNING - Property baz never defined on Bar
  if (this.baz())
      ^
0 error(s), 1 warning(s), 91.7% typed

java -jar ~/closure/compiler.jar --warning_level VERBOSE --js Source/WebCore/inspector/front-end/Foo.js

With following Foo.js:
=======8<=======
/** @constructor */
function Foo() {}

/**
 * @constructor
 * @extends {Foo}
 */
function Bar() {
  Foo.call(this)
  if (this.baz())
    alert(1);
}

Bar.prototype = {
    baz: function()
    {
        return true;
    }
}

Bar.prototype.__proto__ = Foo.prototype;
=======>8=======

Closure Compiler (http://code.google.com/closure/compiler)
Version: 1346
Built on: 2011/08/11 15:02
Mac OS X

We are getting the warnings due to the __proto__ assignment as above again. We decided to move to the prototype = {
    __proto__: 
}
syntax, but I wonder if we are not alone.
